05:44.887 --> 06:05.295
♪  ♪

06:07.661 --> 06:09.194
“Your memory
is a monster.

06:09.994 --> 06:12.498
“It summons with will
of its own.

06:12.500 --> 06:16.033
You think you have a memory,
but it has you.”

06:16.035 --> 06:17.569
John Irving.

06:17.571 --> 06:20.703
Why don't we just start
with the simplest explanation?

06:20.705 --> 06:21.840
They're lying.

06:21.842 --> 06:24.240
There are easier lies
to tell to cover for murder.

06:24.242 --> 06:26.912
Why tell the same one, especially
when it doesn't make sense?

06:26.914 --> 06:28.311
Could it be
a group delusion?

06:28.313 --> 06:30.615
Their similar age range
all points in that direction,

06:30.617 --> 06:31.804
33 to 34 years old,

06:31.828 --> 06:34.026
but the geographic diversity
kind of rules that out.

06:34.090 --> 06:36.717
Yeah. Larry Merrin's
from Topeka.

06:36.719 --> 06:39.085
Christine McNeil is from
Roswell, Georgia,

06:39.087 --> 06:41.495
Daniel Karras
is from Derry, Maine,

06:41.497 --> 06:43.761
all different economic
levels, social circles,

06:43.763 --> 06:45.931
obviously different
racial backgrounds.

06:45.933 --> 06:48.499
So if he's an unsub,
he's not killing but creating killers.

06:48.501 --> 06:50.970
Murder by proxy,
if you will.

06:50.972 --> 06:52.304
It's gotta be drugs.

06:52.306 --> 06:54.239
Larry Merrin's story
just sounds like a bad trip.

06:54.241 --> 06:56.774
According to the police reports,
all 3 tox screens came up negative.

06:56.776 --> 06:58.440
Well, they only screen
for known compounds.

06:58.442 --> 07:00.280
This could be a cocktail
we've never seen before.

07:00.282 --> 07:02.448
Every drug affects
every person differently,

07:02.450 --> 07:05.121
yet somehow this unsub
is able to make his drug

07:05.123 --> 07:08.617
affect 3 completely dissimilar people
exactly in the same way.

07:08.619 --> 07:10.121
Maybe they're not
dissimilar at all.

07:10.123 --> 07:11.793
Maybe the drugs are
just the tipping point

07:11.795 --> 07:14.657
and these 3 share some
sort of pre-existing mental condition

07:14.659 --> 07:17.331
he knows he can tap into
to induce them to kill.

07:17.333 --> 07:20.405
We find that, we find him.

07:27.176 --> 07:30.980
Did she feel a lot of pain?

07:30.982 --> 07:33.750
Did I kill her quickly?

07:34.858 --> 07:37.992
Mr. Karras, we want to get
to the bottom of this, too.

07:37.994 --> 07:41.064
So we'd like to take you through
a cognitive interview.

07:42.034 --> 07:43.464
What's the point?

07:43.466 --> 07:46.465
It could help you remember details
you couldn't before.

07:46.467 --> 07:50.541
And those details could help us
understand what happened.

07:50.543 --> 07:52.077
So, please.

07:53.545 --> 07:56.247
Close your eyes.

07:59.786 --> 08:04.128
And put yourself
back in your home a week ago.

08:04.130 --> 08:08.158
You got home from
work early, right?

08:08.160 --> 08:10.063
Right.

08:10.065 --> 08:13.471
How did you feel when you walked
through the door?

08:15.537 --> 08:17.038
Happy.

08:20.313 --> 08:22.807
Hey, Ma.

08:22.809 --> 08:24.342
Hey, Ma, you home?

08:24.344 --> 08:26.612
She wasn't.
And then I remembered

08:26.614 --> 08:31.146
she said that she was
going to the movies with some friends.

08:31.148 --> 08:33.148
I thought my beer
tasted funny.

08:33.150 --> 08:35.486
And then I realized
it wasn't my beer,

08:35.489 --> 08:37.792
that it was a smell that was coming
from somewhere else.

08:37.794 --> 08:39.328
What was the smell?

08:39.331 --> 08:40.866
Sage.

08:42.931 --> 08:44.967
You're sure about that?

08:44.969 --> 08:49.503
Yeah. Yeah, because
once I placed it,

08:49.505 --> 08:51.175
I was out.

08:53.410 --> 08:56.312
How long
were you out?

08:56.314 --> 08:57.616
I don't know.

08:57.618 --> 08:59.617
All I know
is that when I came to,

08:59.619 --> 09:02.720
it was dark
and I couldn't move.

09:10.195 --> 09:12.097
Help!

09:15.331 --> 09:17.401
Somebody help me!

09:17.403 --> 09:19.505
Help!

09:36.687 --> 09:39.388
It did sexual things to me.

09:53.835 --> 09:59.035
He had these--these--
these talons for hands,

09:59.037 --> 10:01.002
and...

10:05.304 --> 10:09.510
Uh, I got--I got free
and then I, um...

10:09.512 --> 10:12.045
And then I hid
somewhere in the house,

10:12.047 --> 10:14.613
and, uh...

10:15.718 --> 10:17.012
Next thing I remember,

10:17.014 --> 10:19.052
I was standing over
my mom's body...

10:22.724 --> 10:25.618
And the cops
were cuffing me.

10:27.060 --> 10:29.057
I...

10:29.059 --> 10:32.055
So...So, I--

10:32.057 --> 10:34.927
maybe--maybe--you know,
maybe the rape,

10:34.929 --> 10:36.800
you know, uh...

10:36.802 --> 10:38.264
Maybe I snapped.

10:38.266 --> 10:40.103
You know?
You know what I mean?

10:40.105 --> 10:42.869
Maybe I snapped
and, uh, I lashed out

10:42.871 --> 10:44.605
at the first person
that I saw.

10:44.607 --> 10:46.237
Mr. Karras--

10:46.239 --> 10:47.806
because this is the only
way that it makes sense.

10:47.808 --> 10:49.174
At your lawyer's insistence,
the Maine police

10:49.176 --> 10:50.543
ran a rape kit on you.

10:50.545 --> 10:53.783
There was no evidence of assault,
sexual or otherwise.

10:53.785 --> 10:56.487
Ok, well,
run another rape kit.

10:56.489 --> 10:59.621
No rope burns
on your arms or legs.

10:59.623 --> 11:01.149
No evidence
of a break-in at all.

11:01.151 --> 11:02.388
What you guys trying
to tell me,

11:02.390 --> 11:05.753
that this didn't happen
to me? 'Cause it did!

11:13.365 --> 11:15.498
There are others.

11:15.500 --> 11:16.961
Excuse me?

11:16.963 --> 11:20.600
My lawyer said that there were others
that this happened to.

11:20.602 --> 11:22.566
That's right.

11:22.568 --> 11:25.500
Well, can I talk to them?

11:25.502 --> 11:27.900
No.

11:27.902 --> 11:29.801
Why not?

11:39.544 --> 11:41.878
Christine?

11:41.880 --> 11:43.953
Christine?

11:45.219 --> 11:46.719
Can you just blink

11:46.721 --> 11:49.683
if you understand
what we're saying?

11:51.156 --> 11:53.687
Georgia police say
that she started to tell the story

11:53.689 --> 11:55.950
of being attacked
by a dark figure

11:55.952 --> 11:58.116
and then stopped
and started doing this.

11:58.118 --> 12:00.586
Can you blame her?

12:00.588 --> 12:03.090
Sir. I'm sorry,
it's urgent.

12:03.092 --> 12:04.857
No, it's all right.

12:04.859 --> 12:06.257
Do what you can.

12:06.259 --> 12:09.424
Yeah, sure.
I'll just, uh...

12:12.665 --> 12:13.959
I did some digging.

12:13.961 --> 12:16.200
All 3 of our victims
were adopted

12:16.202 --> 12:17.832
and all in 1985.
All of them.

12:17.834 --> 12:19.135
From where?

12:19.137 --> 12:21.101
That's the thing.
It's from different states,

12:21.103 --> 12:22.973
they were closed adoptions,
it's pre-Internet.

12:22.975 --> 12:25.470
I gotta go through
the analog rabbit hole.

12:25.472 --> 12:26.639
It'll take a while.

12:26.641 --> 12:28.208
All right, Rossi and Reid
just landed in Topeka

12:28.210 --> 12:29.815
to walk the crime scene,
and I want you to reach out

12:29.817 --> 12:32.150
to the family members and find out
if there's any shared history

12:32.152 --> 12:33.981
In the foster care system.
Sir, yes, sir.

12:33.983 --> 12:35.316
Thank you.

12:41.789 --> 12:45.155
No records or paperwork in the house
regarding Larry Merrin's adoption.

12:45.157 --> 12:46.828
Morgan struck out
with the vics.

12:46.830 --> 12:47.997
They knew
they were adopted

12:47.999 --> 12:49.495
but couldn't
recall anything.

12:49.497 --> 12:51.333
Well, they were 3 to 4
years old at the time.

12:51.335 --> 12:54.700
Firm memories don't imprint on the
developing brain until about age 5.

12:54.702 --> 12:57.603
Yet somehow the unsub
was able to make the victims

12:57.605 --> 13:00.603
hallucinate an almost primal
childhood fear of the dark

13:00.605 --> 13:02.812
and of the monsters
that lurk within it.

13:02.814 --> 13:05.307
Yeah, but how?
This place was locked up tight.

13:05.309 --> 13:07.644
Well, both men reported
smelling sage.

13:07.646 --> 13:09.981
They must have inhaled
a drug.

13:09.983 --> 13:11.989
They had to
breathe it in.

13:30.782 --> 13:32.448
Anything?

13:39.395 --> 13:43.098
The plastic tested positive
for sevoflurane and scopolamine,

13:43.100 --> 13:45.001
both powerful
disassociatives.

13:45.003 --> 13:47.503
The first is used
to put you into a waking dream.

13:47.505 --> 13:49.670
Dentists often use it
during oral surgery.

13:49.672 --> 13:52.974
The second, in high doses,
makes you completely suggestible.

13:52.976 --> 13:56.235
And the unsub uses the first to make
the victims hallucinate their worst fear.

13:56.237 --> 13:58.443
Then he uses the second
to make them attack that fear

13:58.445 --> 14:00.275
when it's really
the person next to them.

14:00.277 --> 14:02.709
They don't realize that they're actually
killing someone that they love.

14:02.711 --> 14:04.950
And once they do, their
lives are ruined forever.

14:04.952 --> 14:07.053
Even if they plead insanity,
we've got 3 victims

14:07.055 --> 14:09.085
who ain't never
goin' back to Mayberry.

14:09.087 --> 14:11.389
Let's go back to the part
about hallucinating your worst fear.

14:11.391 --> 14:13.093
JJ, what's your earliest
fear from childhood?

14:13.095 --> 14:15.125
Being separated
from my parents.

14:15.127 --> 14:16.157
Dave?

14:16.159 --> 14:17.725
Lon Chaney,
“Phantom of the Opera.”

14:17.727 --> 14:19.165
she takes off that mask,
forget about it.

14:19.167 --> 14:20.133
Kate?

14:20.135 --> 14:22.133
Melissa Gordner.
That bitch.

14:22.135 --> 14:25.135
And yet each of these
victims saw exactly the same thing.

14:25.137 --> 14:28.073
The initial police reports
only called it a dark figure,

14:28.075 --> 14:30.314
but our interviews revealed
shared details.

14:30.316 --> 14:32.979
A shadow monster
with talons for hands.

14:32.981 --> 14:34.387
And that level
of specificity says

14:34.389 --> 14:35.987
it's not just
a childhood nightmare,

14:35.989 --> 14:37.491
it's something they
actually experienced,

14:37.493 --> 14:39.291
though they were too young
to understand what it was.

14:39.293 --> 14:41.027
But they were
from different states.

14:41.029 --> 14:42.323
No, they were adopted in
different states.

14:42.325 --> 14:44.258
Maybe at some point
they shared the same group home.

14:44.260 --> 14:46.666
So the unsub has them
recall that memory from childhood

14:46.668 --> 14:49.667
to make them kill as adults.
How do we prove it?

14:56.144 --> 14:59.417
Can you draw me
what you saw?

15:45.862 --> 15:47.229
Dad?

15:47.231 --> 15:48.661
Huh?

15:48.663 --> 15:50.936
Bogeyman's in my room again.

15:50.938 --> 15:52.276
There's no such thing.

15:52.278 --> 15:54.342
Go to bed.

15:54.344 --> 15:56.584
Will you check?

16:00.454 --> 16:03.358
Come on.

16:09.170 --> 16:11.673
Is there a bogeyman in here?

16:11.675 --> 16:15.471
If there is,
you have to leave.

16:20.679 --> 16:23.675
How about down here?

16:23.677 --> 16:26.881
Cast him out, Dad.

16:26.883 --> 16:28.512
Bogeyman,

16:28.514 --> 16:31.413
I cast you out!

16:31.415 --> 16:33.716
I think we're good.

16:39.357 --> 16:41.691
Do you have
a bogeyman, Dad?

16:41.693 --> 16:46.660
Yeah. He's called FICA
and he haunts my paycheck.

16:46.662 --> 16:48.995
Yeah, don't worry about that.

16:48.997 --> 16:53.270
Listen, we can't do this
every night, Bud.

16:53.272 --> 16:55.776
I can't help it.

17:02.950 --> 17:08.019
Are you and mom
ever gonna live together again?

17:10.492 --> 17:12.561
I don't know.

17:12.564 --> 17:14.058
I want to.

17:14.060 --> 17:16.630
Why don't you?

17:16.632 --> 17:19.661
Because sometimes
dads make mistakes.

17:19.663 --> 17:21.763
And I'm trying
to do everything I can

17:21.766 --> 17:24.497
to fix that mistake
with your mom.

17:28.800 --> 17:29.965
Go to sleep.

18:27.319 --> 18:29.149
We sure this is
the same unsub?

18:29.151 --> 18:32.391
Garcia set up a search parameter
for closed adoptions.

18:32.393 --> 18:35.329
Bill Kinderman
was adopted May 5, 1985.

18:35.331 --> 18:37.666
The M.E. said this victim
slit his own throat.

18:37.668 --> 18:39.499
That's a big change in M.O.

18:39.501 --> 18:42.306
Well, what if that
wasn't the unsub?

18:42.308 --> 18:44.339
What if that was Bill?

18:44.341 --> 18:47.210
So the only other person
in the apartment was his son,

18:47.212 --> 18:49.011
who slept through
the whole thing.

18:49.013 --> 18:51.916
What if the unsub
tried to get him to kill his son,

18:51.918 --> 18:55.388
but his paternal instinct
trumped the effects of the drugs?

18:55.390 --> 18:58.386
Thank God for that,
but we're still at square zero.

18:58.388 --> 19:01.057
This unsub committed
4 murders in 4 states.

19:01.059 --> 19:03.720
How is he connecting
these victims so quickly?

19:03.722 --> 19:05.927
Well, that is what Hotch
is trying to figure out right now

19:05.929 --> 19:08.055
with Kinderman's ex-wife.

19:08.057 --> 19:10.959
No. I mean, yes,
Bill knew he was adopted,

19:10.961 --> 19:14.063
but it was closed.

19:14.065 --> 19:16.233
He didn't know anything
about his past.

19:16.235 --> 19:19.211
Neither did his parents.

19:19.213 --> 19:20.907
Two other victims
drew these.

19:20.909 --> 19:23.874
They were both adopted,
possibly from the same house.

19:23.876 --> 19:25.711
Did he ever talk about
anything like this?

19:25.713 --> 19:28.677
No. I mean, he made up
all sorts of other stories,

19:28.679 --> 19:30.477
but nothing about that.

19:30.479 --> 19:32.244
What do you mean?

19:34.453 --> 19:39.155
